<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>integerrimus</i> is dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>manzanita</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>patula</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>cordulatus</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>cuneatus</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>velutinus</i>, <i>Chamaebatia</i> <i>foliolosa</i>, <i>Holodiscus</i> <i>discolor</i>, <i>Lotus</i> <i>crassifolius</i>, <i>Prunus</i> <i>emarginata</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>berberidifolia</i> and <i>Symphoricarpos</i> <i>mollis</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Pinus</i> <i>ponderosa</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>chrysolepis</i> or <i>Quercus</i> <i>wislizeni</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 4 m; canopy is continuous or intermittent. Herbaceous layer is sparse to intermittent. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Ceanothus integerrimus</i> > 50% relative cover in shrub canopy (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
		
		<li><i>Ceanothus integerrimus</i> > 30% relative cover in shrub canopy (Klein et al. 2007).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Ridges and upper slopes. Soils are well drained.  </div>
</div>

        
