<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus integerrimus </i>is a winter-deciduous or semi-deciduous shrub with flexible branches that grows to 6 m in height. The roots harbor nitrogen-fixing bacteria. At 4 years. shrubs begin producing seed, which is explosively cast from the plant as the capsule breaks. Most of the seed drops beneath the crowns of the shrub, collecting in the duff and soil as a seed bank. An estimate of 2 million seeds per hectare was made for the seed bank under a mixed conifer forest (Howard 1997a). <br/>
<br/>
Several varieties of <i>C. integerrimus </i>(var. <i>californicus, </i>var. <i>integerrimus, </i>var. <i>macrothyrsus, </i>and var. <i>puberulus</i>) have been recognized by Hickman (1993) or elsewhere. They show some geographic separation, but differences may be in response to environmental variation. Fross and Wilken (2006) reduced the number of varieties to plants with one (var. <i>integerrimus</i>) or three (var. <i>macrothyrsus</i>) prominent veins from leaf blade bases. We include these two in this alliance. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Ceanothus integerrimus </i>occurs as scattered to dense shrubs in the understory of forests or in shrublands at several elevation zones and sections of the state. Selfperpetuating stands are very unusual; instead, stands are usually established after fire, logging, or other disturbances. They are transitional to various conifer and oak forest types. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
