<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Ceanothus integerrimus </i>rapidly sprouts from root crowns when branches are burned or removed. When plants are top-killed before they become decadent, the roots remain alive; without periodic top-kill, decadent plants die (Griffin 1982). Heat from fire and increased light after fire stimulate seed germination of <i>C. integerrimus </i>by increasing permeability to water. Best seedling establishment occurs in bare mineral soil. Shrub stands grow quickly for about four decades and then become senescent (Howard 1997a).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
