    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aj-k). Stands follow burns in the forest belt of the Santa Lucia Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ae). Stands from recent burns exist in the eastern Santa Lucia Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa, Ac-l, An-u). Stands develop after fires and logging at Castle Crags State Park (Stuart et al. 1993) and other parts of the eastern Klamath Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gf, Gi-j, Gl, Go). Stands occur in openings and forest clearings in the Warner and other higher mountains of the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Am). Stands occur near Mount Saint Helena.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba-b, Bd-f). Stands grow after fire and logging throughout the section at montane elevations, including those at Hale Ridge RNA (Cheng 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-h, Em, Ep, Er-s). Stands occur after fires and logging at montane elevations. Large stands occupy some of the recent burns in lower-elevation mixed conifer forest types adjacent to Yosemite (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) and Sequoia national parks (S. Haultain, pers. comm. 2003).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). Stands occur across the section; they often occur in post-burn chaparral and oak types in the northernmost subsection above 400 m, especially on volcanic substrate (Klein et al. 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-b, Bd-e, Bg-h, Bm, Bo). Stands resulting from recent burns are found at higher elevations, including the Cuyamaca, San Bernardino, San Jacinto, San Gabriel, and San Rafael mountains, and near Hot Springs Mountain. Descriptions exist from Big Pine Mountain, Cleghorn Canyon, Fern Canyon, and Hall Canyon RNAs (Cheng 2004), the western San Gabriel and southern San Bernardino mountains (Gordon and White 1994), Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b), and Volcan Mountain area (Evens and San 2005). There appears to be zonation between at least three species of re-seeding <i>Ceanothus species</i> following crown fires in coniferous and hardwood forests in the mountains of San Diego Co. Stands of <i>C. integerrimus</i> occupy the highest elevation/coolest sites; those of <i>C. oliganthus</i> modal sites; and those of <i>C. leucodermis</i> at the lowest-elevation/warmest sites.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da, Dd-g, Di-j, Dl-m). Stands develop after fires and logging at montane elevations, including those at Iron Mountain RNA (Cheng 2004).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Plantation conifers generally grow slower with <i>Ceanothus integerrimus </i>removed (Howard 1997a), and the presences of shrubs do not adversely affect natural conifer regeneration (Griffin 1982). In addition, establishment of conifers such as <i>Pinus lambertiana </i>and <i>P. coulteri </i>has been more successful in the presence of <i>C. integerrimus </i>after stand-replacing wildfire. Fires also perpetuate a mosaic of age classes in chaparral and forest landscapes, decreasing the chances for widespread fires (Howard 1997a). 

<i>Ceanothus integerrimus </i>provides high-quality, palatable, and often abundant forage for livestock and wildlife, especially deer. It is also recommended for use on restoration projects due to its nitrogen-fixing ability (Howard 1997a). </div>
</div>

    

    

